'''Tenjin Shrine''' (てんじんじんじゃ) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|WD=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} in Yanaizu-chō (former {{ill|lt=Yanaizu, Gifu|Q8048244|WD=Q8048244|lt=Yanaizu Town|1=Yanaizu, Gifu}}, {{ill|lt=Hashima District|Q615068|WD=Q615068|1=Hashima District, Gifu}}), {{ill|lt=Gifu|Q45798|WD=Q45798|1=Gifu}}, {{ill|lt=Gifu Prefecture|Q131277|WD=Q131277|1=Gifu Prefecture}}. It is also called Yanaizu Tenjin Shrine.

It is Anahobe Shrine of Haguri District, {{ill|lt=Owari Province|Q514506|WD=Q514506|1=Owari Province}}, in the {{ill|lt=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|Q11064932|WD=Q11064932|lt=Engishiki|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}} (there is also a theory that Anahobe Shrine is {{ill|lt=Kamo Shrine (Ichinomiya)|Q11634949|WD=Q11634949|lt=Kamo Shrine|1=Kamo Shrine (Ichinomiya)}} in Ichinomiya, Aichi).

The current Tenjin Shrine is a merged shrine of Anahobe Shrine, Kita-Tenjin Shrine, and Naka-Tenjin Shrine.

=== Outline ===
*The founding time of Anahobe Shrine is unclear, but one account says it was founded in the 6th century as the guardian shrine of Taishi-dera (present {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Kōtaku-ji|1=UNKNOWN}}), founded by {{ill|lt=Prince Shōtoku|Q263972|WD=Q263972|1=Prince Shōtoku}}. The enshrined deity was {{ill|UNKNOWN|WD=Q10940685|lt=Ame-no-Hohi-no-Mikoto|1=Ame no Hohi}}. The location is said to have been about 500 m south of the current Tenjin Shrine. In the {{ill|lt=Edo period|Q184963|WD=Q184963|1=Edo period}} it was called “Akata Tenjin” and was the guardian shrine of Kōtaku-ji, but became independent through {{ill|lt=separation of Shinto and Buddhism|Q1970535|WD=Q1970535|1=Shinbutsu bunri}} in the {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Meiji period|1=Meiji era|WD=Q3125096}}.
*Kita-Tenjin Shrine was founded in {{ill|lt=1557|Q6595|WD=Q6595|1=1557}} ({{ill|lt=Kōji (Japan)|Q1143910|WD=Q1143910|lt=Kōji|1=Kōji (Muromachi period)}} 3) by descendants of Minamoto no Yorizane (or Minamoto no Yorisada), enshrining an image of Sugawara no Michizane made by him; its deity was {{ill|lt=Sugawara no Michizane|Q382005|WD=Q382005|1=Sugawara no Michizane}}. Naka-Tenjin Shrine has an unknown foundation date.
*In {{ill|lt=1945|Q5240|WD=Q5240|1=1945}} (Shōwa 20), Anahobe Shrine and Naka-Tenjin Shrine were merged into Kita-Tenjin Shrine, and in {{ill|lt=1954|Q18581|WD=Q18581|1=1954}} (Shōwa 29) it was renamed Tenjin Shrine. On August 17, {{ill|lt=1965|Q2650|WD=Q2650|1=1965}} (Shōwa 40), it was designated by the Gifu Prefecture Association of Shinto Shrines as a prefectural shinto association chief-visit designated shrine ({{ill|lt=Kinpeisha|Q119929592|WD=Q119929592|1=Kinpei-sha}}), designation No. Kin-63{{sfn|Kimura|1997|p=91}}{{sfn|Gifu Prefecture Association of Shinto Shrines|2017|p=379}}.

